            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Abramov\u2019s sense of purpose was forged in the fog of San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District. The only child of Soviet Jewish immigrants who arrived in the 1980s, David grew up listening to stories of hardship and resilience. His parents\u2014a watchmaker and a seamstress\u2014instilled in him a profound gratitude for the community organizations that helped them navigate a new language and culture. He saw firsthand how a local non-profit provided them with legal aid and job training, a formative experience that planted the seed for his future career.\n\nHe stayed local for college, attending San Francisco State University, where a Bachelor's in Social Work felt less like a choice and more like a calling. Graduating in the wake of the 2008 recession, he dove into the challenging world of frontline case management, working with at-risk youth in the Mission District. The burnout was high, but David\u2019s calm demeanor and deep empathy made him effective. A key turning point came when he helped a newly arrived immigrant family secure healthcare for their chronically ill child, a situation that mirrored his own parents\u2019 early struggles. This solidified his resolve, and he began focusing on systemic solutions rather than individual cases.\n\nNow 36, David is the Program Director for a well-respected non-profit in SoMa. His $115,000 salary affords him a modest, rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment in the Panhandle, a neighborhood he loves for its proximity to Golden Gate Park and its diverse community. His daily routine is grounded: a morning coffee from a local cafe, followed by a 3.5-mile commute on the Muni bus, where he listens to podcasts on urban policy. His social life revolves around a tight-knit group of friends, many of whom also work in public service. They prefer low-key brewery nights and weekend hikes in Marin to the city's glitzier scene.\n\nDeeply connected to San Francisco's soul, David is frustrated by its deepening inequalities but remains stubbornly optimistic. His dream is not of wealth, but of impact\u2014to expand his program\u2019s reach and build a more robust support system for the city\u2019s vulnerable populations. He hopes to one day find a long-term partner who shares his values, remaining a quiet anchor in the turbulent, ever-changing city he has always called home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of the Jewish Family and Children\u2019s Services office on Balboa Street\u2014old paper, strong tea, and his mother\u2019s nervous perfume. He was seven, kicking his legs on a vinyl chair, watching a kind-faced woman patiently explain a housing form. He didn\u2019t understand the words, but he understood the relief that washed over his parents\u2019 faces. It wasn\u2019t just a form; it was a lifeline. That day, he learned that practical kindness was a language anyone could understand, a lesson that became his life\u2019s compass.\n\n2.\nAt 16, he sat at a small wooden desk in their Richmond apartment, watching his father repair a vintage watch. Under the bright lamp, his father\u2019s hands were impossibly steady, nudging tiny, intricate gears into place. When the balance wheel began to beat again\u2014a quiet, persistent rhythm\u2014a sense of profound respect filled David. He realized that mending what was broken, whether a timepiece or a community, required patience, precision, and an unwavering belief that things could be made to work again.\n\n3.\nThe victory that defined his twenties wasn\u2019t a promotion, but a phone call. He was a burnt-out case manager in the Mission, fighting for a newly arrived family. After weeks of dead ends, he finally heard a Medi-Cal representative say, \u201cThe child\u2019s coverage is approved.\u201d He relayed the news to the mother, whose sob of pure, unadulterated relief cracked through the receiver. In that moment, the exhaustion vanished, replaced by a fierce clarity. Individual victories were not enough; he had to fix the system itself.\n\n4.\nThe first night in his Panhandle apartment was quiet. He was 29. He had no couch, just a box of books and a sleeping bag on the floor. Through the open window, he could hear the distant rumble of the N-Judah and the foghorns out on the bay. Laying there, he felt a sense of rootedness he\u2019d never known. This wasn\u2019t his parents\u2019 city of refuge anymore, or a college town. It was *his*. This small, rent-controlled square was his anchor, securing him to the home he loved.\n\n5.\nLast year, on a hike in the Marin Headlands, his friends were lamenting the latest city budget cuts. As they spoke, the fog parted, revealing the entire impossible, beautiful skyline. A wave of stubborn love for San Francisco washed over David. He saw the city not just for its flaws, but for its promise\u2014a promise held in the hands of the people beside him. It wasn't a blind optimism, but a shared resolve. Looking at that view, he knew he wasn\u2019t alone in trying to keep it safe."
